6-9:Moreover, the algorithms have been mostly tested over long queries stated in plain English and retrieval for such queries is more robust against speech recognition errors .
6-10:An alternative approach consists of using word lattices in order to improve the effectiveness of SDR .
6-11:Singhal et al .
6-12:[24, 25] propose to add some terms to the transcript in order to alleviate the retrieval failures due to ASR errors .
6-13:From an IR perspective, a classical way to bring new terms is document expansion using a similar corpus .
6-14:Their approach consists in using word lattices in order to determine which words returned by a document expansion algorithm should be added to the original transcript .
6-15:The necessity to use a document expansion algorithm was justified by the fact that the word lattices they worked with, lack information about word probabilities .
6-16:Chelba and Acero in [8, 9] propose a more compact word lattice, the position specific posterior lattice .
6-17:This data structure is similar to WCN and leads to a more compact index .
6-18:The offset of the terms in the speech documents is also stored in the index .
6-19:However, the evaluation framework is carried out on lectures that are relatively planned, in contrast to conversational speech .
6-20:Their ranking model is based on the term confidence level but does not take into consideration the rank of the term among the other hypotheses .
6-21:Mamou et al .
6-22:[17] propose a model for spoken document retrieval using WCNs in order to improve the recall and the MAP of the search .
6-23:However, in the above works, the problem of queries containing OOV terms is not addressed .
6-24:Popular approaches to deal with OOV queries are based on sub words transcripts, where the sub words are typically phones, syllables or word fragments (sequences of phones) [11, 20, 23] .
6-25:The classical approach consists of using phonetic transcripts .
6-26:The transcripts are indexed in the same manner as words in using classical text retrieval techniques; during query processing, the query is represented as a sequence of phones .
6-27:The retrieval is based on searching the string of phones representing the query in the phonetic transcript .
6-28:To account for the high recognition error rates, some other systems use richer transcripts like phonetic lattices .
6-29:They are attractive as they accommodate high error rate conditions as well as allow for OOV queries to be used [15, 3, 20, 23, 21, 27] .
6-30:However, phonetic lattices contain many edges that overlap in time with the same phonetic label, and are difficult to index .
6-31:Moreover, beside the improvement in the recall of the search, the precision is affected since phonetic lattices are often inaccurate .
6-32:Consequently, phonetic approaches should be used only for OOV search; for searching queries containing also IV terms, this technique affects the performance of the retrieval in comparison to the word based approach .
6-33:Saraclar and Sproat in [22] show improvement in word spotting accuracy for both IV and OOV queries, using phonetic and word lattices, where a confidence measure of a word or a phone can be derived .
6-34:They propose three different retrieval strategies: search both the word and the phonetic indices and unify the two different sets of results; search the word index for IV queries, search the phonetic index for OOV queries; search the word index and if no result is returned, search the phonetic index .
6-35:However, no strategy is proposed to deal with phrase queries containing both IV and OOV terms .
6-36:Amir et al .
6-37:in [5, 4] propose to merge a word approach with a phonetic approach in the context of video retrieval .
6-38:However, the phonetic transcript is obtained from a text to phonetic conversion of the 1 best path of the word transcript and is not based on a phonetic decoding of the speech data .
6-39:An important issue to be considered when looking at the state of the art in retrieval of spoken data, is the lack of a common test set and appropriate query terms .
6-40:This paper uses such a task and the STD evaluation is a good summary of the performance of different approaches on the same test conditions. .
7 CONCLUSIONS :
7-1:This work studies how vocabulary independent spoken term detection can be performed efficiently over different data sources .
7-2:Previously, phonetic based and word based approaches have been used for IR on speech data .
7-3:The former suffers from low accuracy and the latter from limited vocabulary of the recognition system .
7-4:In this paper, we have presented a vocabulary independent model of indexing and search that combines both the approaches .
7-5:The system can deal with all kinds of queries although the phrases that need to combine for the retrieval, information extracted from two different indices, a word index and a phonetic index .
7-6:The scoring of OOV terms is based on the proximity (in time) between the different phones .
7-7:The scoring of IV terms is based on information provided by the WCNs .
7-8:We have shown an improvement in the retrieval performance when using all the WCN and not only the 1 best path and when using phonetic index for search of OOV query terms .
7-9:This approach always outperforms the other approaches using only word index or phonetic index .
7-10:As a future work, we will compare our model for OOV search on phonetic transcripts with a retrieval model based on the edit distance. .
